[
    {
        "content": "<p>I've been considering some 2-categorical aspects of 1-topos theory, and it seems to me that the literature is rather limited on this subject. It's not clear <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/342137/95129\">what the (pseudo)-monomorphisms are</a>, for example. There's Section B of the Elephant which deals with some issues of weighted limits and colimits, but that similarly leaves some basic questions unanswered.<br>\nI have shown, for example, that geometric inclusions are full and faithful in the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathfrak{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.88047em;vertical-align:-0.18906em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">p</span></span></span></span></span> of toposes, and that localic geometric morphisms are faithful. Is this a known fact? Is the converse known? I'm leaning towards the conjecture that the surjection-inclusion and hyperconnected-localic factorisation systems correspond to the (eso,ff) and (eso+full,faithful) factorisation systems, but there's some more work to do to verify that. If it's <em>not</em> the case, that could be quite exciting.<br>\nIt is never stated explicitly in the Elephant that geometric surjections are stable under pullback, so even if the above is true, it's still unclear whether <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathfrak{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.88047em;vertical-align:-0.18906em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">p</span></span></span></span></span> is a (locally) <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/michaelshulman/show/regular+2-category\">regular 2-category</a>.<br>\n<span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277180\">@Simon Henry</span>, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span>, since I'm referring to your answer and blog respectively, do you have any further insights?</p>",
        "id": 223361688,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1611142354
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh I <a href=\"https://math.stackexchange.com/q/3992838/354508\">worked out</a> why surjections aren't stable under pullback, at least, so indeed there's no chance of local regularity if my preceding conjecture holds.</p>",
        "id": 223376911,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1611152020
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have also worked out that surjections are co-faithful, but unless I find a way to show that the ff morphisms in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathfrak{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.88047em;vertical-align:-0.18906em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">p</span></span></span></span></span> are <em>precisely</em> the inclusions, it will be impossible to verify that surjections are precisely the eso morphisms according to <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/eso+morphism\">the pullback definition</a>.</p>",
        "id": 223377520,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1611152316
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't remember whether I've seen it written down explicitly that geometric inclusions are ff and localic morphisms are faithful, but the first one is pretty obvious and I remember observing the latter myself.  But I don't think that these factorization systems coincide with (eso,ff) and (eso+full,faithful); it's better to think of the 2-category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathfrak{Topos}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.88047em;vertical-align:-0.18906em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">p</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">s</span></span></span></span></span> as analogous to the 1-category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">p</span></span></span></span></span> of topological spaces (or, better, the 1-category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Loc}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">c</span></span></span></span></span> of locales), in which not every monomorphism is is a subspace inclusion.</p>",
        "id": 223392722,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1611158184
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you haven't read it already, you might be interested in section 5.4 of <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0608420\">Lectures on n-Categories and Cohomology</a>.</p>",
        "id": 223392827,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1611158236
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for the response Mike! Those notes (especially the subsequent Section 5.5) have reinforced the intuition I was developing through your blog that the range of notions of monicness expands naturally with the dimension one is working in.<br>\n<span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/2-category.20of.20toposes/near/223392722\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>it's better to think of the 2-category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathfrak{Topos}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.88047em;vertical-align:-0.18906em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">p</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak\">s</span></span></span></span></span> as analogous to the 1-category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Top}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">p</span></span></span></span></span> of topological spaces (or, better, the 1-category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Loc}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">c</span></span></span></span></span> of locales), in which not every monomorphism is is a subspace inclusion.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I know this fact, and the stackexchange link I mentioned earlier contains a specific counterexample to it. The problem is that saying \"not every <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>\" doesn't answer the question of precisely which <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> are <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> ! I'll keep chipping away at this.</p>",
        "id": 223397609,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1611160053
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>fyi <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span>, the pullback squares before Definition 20 in Section 5.5 of those notes seem dodgy! They should have <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>B</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C(B,X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> in the top left corner, I think.</p>",
        "id": 223531216,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1611245755
    },
